The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Opinion | fast and close
                                                                                                                 FAST AND CLOSE                                                    
	The unique selling proposition of the Nizam-i-Adl Regulation 2009 in Swat, for the enforcement of Islamic law, lay not in the intricacies of its grammar but in its efficacy as an instrument of Taliban containment. That is how it was sold to Pakistans gullible public and the world. But the vengeance with which the Taliban have been advancing in Pakistan shows that effecting a judicial revolution is the last thing on their mind. Within a few days, the Taliban have crossed into Buner, consolidated their position there, and begun a recruitment drive. Only a few kilometres now separate them from Islamabad, which continues to retain an unshakeable faith in the Talibans promises of peace, bought at the cost the peoples most basic freedoms. The provocation in Buner had been the assembling of an anti-Taliban lashkar or militia by residents  their last hope in the face of the apathy of the armed forces. But even after driving out the dissenters, the Taliban have stayed on. As in tribal Bajaur, the Taliban version of what constitutes sharia has been quickly enforced in Buner with the attendant smashing of television sets and prohibition of entertainment. The armed forces have remained mute spectators, apparently on the orders of their superiors, who discourage resistance in fear of harming the peace. The last is the residue of the arrangement in Swat which is in tatters following the unexplained recalcitrance of the Pakistan president to put his signature on the legislation. The accord has been dragged to the parliament, and the Awami National Party, which governs the province, sees it as betrayal. In Swat itself, Maulana Fazlullah has managed to upstage his father-in-law, Sufi Mohammad, again.         
	If this does not convince Pakistan of the failure of its containment policy, little else will. The strategy assumes that it is possible to divide the Taliban through bribes and incentives and there are some good Taliban who are willing to buy peace. But as the ground realities of Afpak suggest, the Taliban are already divided into innumerable factions, each trying to steal a march on the others by constantly upping the price of peace by threats of violence (take Baitullah Mehsuds perennial efforts to stay in the limelight). While the walls close in on the people of Pakistan, the government continues to pin its hopes on ephemeral Taliban integrity to forestall the inexorable march of the militia towards Islamabad.                                                                                                                                                                     
